Upon reviewing the Atlassian Customer Agreement, I have identified a provision related to third-party code and third-party products (Section 7). This provision requires Atlassian to include certain terms and conditions in its agreements with third-party providers, including those related to intellectual property rights and liability.

Specifically, Section 7.1 requires Atlassian to include in its agreements with third-party providers a provision that states that the third-party provider's code is provided "as-is" and that Atlassian makes no warranties or representations with respect to the code. Additionally, Section 7.2 requires Atlassian to include in its agreements with third-party providers a provision that limits the third-party provider's liability for damages to the amount paid by Atlassian for the third-party provider's services.

However, I have not found any provisions in the Atlassian Customer Agreement that require the assessment of relationships with closely connected providers. Therefore, I recommend flagging the absence of this requirement and suggesting that the contract be updated to include provisions that evaluate risks from connected providers.

In particular, I suggest adding a clause that requires Atlassian to:

* Identify and document all closely connected providers that provide services or products to Atlassian or its customers;
* Assess the risks associated with these relationships, including the potential for conflicts of interest, data breaches, or other security risks;
* Develop and implement policies and procedures to manage these relationships and mitigate any identified risks;
* Report on the assessment and mitigation of these risks to customers and other stakeholders as required.

By including these provisions, the contract can ensure that Atlassian is taking steps to manage the risks associated with its relationships with closely connected providers and that customers are aware of these risks and the measures being taken to mitigate them.

Compliance officers must ensure that subcontracting chains are transparent and disclosed to customers to maintain trust and accountability. Upon reviewing the Atlassian Customer Agreement, I located Clause 20.11, which addresses subcontractors and affiliates. However, it only mentions that Atlassian may use subcontractors or its affiliates in the performance of its obligations under the Agreement, but it does not provide full disclosure of subcontractors.

To enhance transparency, I suggest adding a provision to Clause 20.11, which requires Atlassian to disclose the following information to customers:

* A list of all subcontractors involved in the performance of the Agreement, including their names, addresses, and roles;
* A description of the services provided by each subcontractor;
* Information about the subcontractor's performance history, including any relevant certifications, licenses, or qualifications;
* A process for customers to request information about subcontractors and to report any concerns or issues related to subcontractors.

This transparency provision will enable customers to make informed decisions about their use of Atlassian's products and services and will help to build trust in the subcontracting chain. The revised clause could read:

"20.11 Subcontractors and Affiliates. Atlassian may use subcontractors or its affiliates in the performance of its obligations under this Agreement. Atlassian will provide customers with a list of all subcontractors involved in the performance of the Agreement, including their names, addresses, and roles. Atlassian will also provide customers with a description of the services provided by each subcontractor and information about the subcontractor's performance history. Customers may request information about subcontractors and report any concerns or issues related to subcontractors to Atlassian. Atlassian will maintain a record of all subcontractors and their performance history and will make this information available to customers upon request."

This revised clause will enhance transparency and accountability in Atlassian's subcontracting chain, ensuring that customers are aware of the entities involved in the performance of the Agreement and can make informed decisions about their use of Atlassian's products and services.
